div2.p:
These People worshipped several
Gods, viz. Jupiter tonans, or Thundering Jupiter, whom they sorely dreaded: Then Anubis latrans,or barking Anubis: Also Mercury an Inventor of Arts, and a prosperer of Journeys;
likewise Andate and  Adraste, Gods of Victory.

England is blest with a sweet and temperate Air;
the Summers (by reason of the continual and gentle winds) so abating the heats, and the thickness of the air, with frequent showers in the Winter so aswaging the cold;
that neither the one, nor the other, are found obnoxious to its Inhabitants:
the Summer not scorching, nor the Winter benumning them.

Its fertility.

div3.p:
Here are belonging to this Court four Judges, or Justices;
viz. Sir Mathew Hales Kt. Lord chief Justice, Sir Thomas Twisden Kt. and Baronet,
Sir Richard Rainsford Kt. and Sir William Morton Kt.

div1.p:
It is bounded on the East with the Counties of Hartsford and
Cambridge;
on the South also with Hartfordshire; on the West with Buckinghamshire;
and on the North with the Counties of Northampton and Huntington.
Its division of Hundreds.

At Mam Torre, the Sand is said continually to
fall down, and yet the hill
not to diminish. Buxton-bath and Chatsworth are the two other wonders,
all comprised in this Verse of Mr. Thomas Hobbes;
ædes, mons, Barathrum, binus fons, antraque bina;
to whose elegant Poem (de mirabilibus Pecci) I refer the Reader.

Raleigh, a place of great antiquity, though not largeness;
and its Market, which is on Saturdays, is but small.
Isles of Wallop and Fowlness.

Axbridge, seated not far from the Chedder-rock,
and under the Mendiphills, very rich in Lead-mines, and also fertile for feeding of cattle;
It is a Maior-town, hath one principal street, which is long, but narrow;
and hath a very considerable Market for corn and provisions on Thursdays.
Glassenbury.

